    pearls: ["Most thyroid nodules (90-95%) are benign — appropriate risk stratification prevents unnecessary surgery","ACR TI-RADS uses 5 ultrasound features to score nodules and determine FNA size thresholds — this is the standard of care for nodule evaluation","TSH is the FIRST test for any thyroid nodule; if suppressed, get RAIU scan before FNA (hot nodules are almost always benign and do not need FNA)","Microcalcifications on ultrasound are the most specific feature for papillary thyroid cancer — small, punctate, hyperechoic foci without posterior shadowing","Thyroid incidentalomas found on CT, MRI, or PET: PET-avid nodules have higher malignancy risk (35-40%) and should be biopsied","TSH suppression therapy for benign nodules is no longer recommended — risks of subclinical hyperthyroidism (AF, osteoporosis) outweigh marginal benefit","Sudden painful enlargement of a thyroid nodule usually indicates hemorrhage into a cyst, not malignancy — obtain ultrasound and manage conservatively"],
